  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 산에 올라[陟岵] : '
    value: 《시경》에 〈척고(陟岵)편〉이 있는데 높은 데 올라 부모를 생각한다는 시다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 종신모(終身慕) : '
    value: 맹자(孟子)의 말에, “종신토록 부모를 생각하는 이는 오직 순(舜)이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 기린아(麒麟兒) : '
    value: 양(梁)나라 문인(文人)  서릉(徐陵)이 처음 났을 때 중 보지(寶誌)가 와서 보고 머리를 어루만지면서, “이 아이는 천상(天上)의 석기린(石麒麟)이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 間 : '
    value: 門
english:
  title: In Praise of the Pavilion of Eternal Reverence
  author: Han Soo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Yuan's son of heaven exalted the supreme order,
    Mountains bowed and seas surrendered from south to north.
    Only Japan stood defiant, refusing to pay homage,
    So we sent envoys to display our virtue and might.

    The court's officials all shrank back in fear,
    Thinking only of themselves, unwilling to venture forth.
    But Gwok Jang-won, our region's gallant hero,
    Had a heart as vast and boundless as heaven and earth.
    Forgetting self to serve his nation—this was his true nature.
    Gladly he accepted the post of imperial scribe,
    Passed through the gates without farewell to wife and child,
    Raised anchor to sail ten thousand leagues across the waves.

    Vast and empty, the sea and sky stretched before him;
    The wild geese's call faded into distance.
    Who could know he bore the mark of honor like Su Wu?
    His son remained alone at home,
    Gazing eastward day and night, his heart burning with longing.
    Clinching the mountain peak, tears blur his sight,
    Crying to heaven, his small heart pooling red blood.

    Heaven took pity on this eternal filial devotion,
    Sending a son of rare grace to attend his father.
    The boy's only wish was to bring ease to his aged parent—
    In warmth and comfort, food and care, nothing was lacking.
    Yet knowing this could never fully please,
    He labored ceaselessly in all he could do.

    A new pavilion rose, perfectly situated,
    Where winter's cold is gentle and summer's heat forgone.
    A pond was dug, fresh spring water channeled through,
    Flowers planted to answer the birds' sweet song.
    Spring winds bring blossoms, autumn moon shines bright,
    All serving to soothe the father's sorrow.

    A hundred years devoted to honoring his parent's wishes,
    Then that filial heart transformed into loyalty to the state.
    He kept to the path of virtue without wavering,
    Even now holding steady to the way.
    Though office never matched the measure of his merit,
    The gentleman harbored no resentment—only others sighed.

    Oh, beacon of our land, exemplar of virtue!
    A master's pen inscribes your deeds upon bamboo and silk.
    Across the four seas live hundreds of millions,
    Yet how few truly fulfill their duty as subjects and sons?
    Know then that the Pavilion of Eternal Reverence spans three generations,
    A model for all the world and ages yet to come.
  footnotes:
    - 'Su Wu (蘇武): A Han dynasty envoy who was captured and held for nineteen years, yet maintained his loyalty and honor throughout, becoming a symbol of steadfast virtue under hardship.'
    - The reference to climbing the mountain alludes to the Classic of Poetry, where one ascends to contemplate distant parents—expressing the son's longing for his father.
    - The 'son of rare grace' (麒麟兒) is a traditional term for an exceptionally gifted and virtuous child, suggesting the son inherited his father's noble character.
